Mr Rakonczay, 30, made the journey without a satellite tracking system which would have allowed him to signal that he was all right.

So his wife, who stayed behind in Hungary, could only hope for the best.

'The supplier raised the price at the last minute and I decided to leave without one because it was not possible to postpone the trip,' Mr Rakonczay said from Nelson's Dockyard in southern Antigua.

'This trip was the first time I didn't have a tracking system and the first time I really would have needed one.'

During the nearly seven weeks he was out of reach, Viktoria, his wife, gave no indications that she was anything but totally sure that her husband was alive and that only equipment failure was to blame for their lack of communication.

